title: For Sale:  Exc. Taurus PT92 w/ 3 mags, 2 grips and case
postcontent:
Up for sale is this really nice 1992 PT92 AF-D. The PT92 is an improved version of the original 1975 Beretta 92 that Beretta produced in Brazil until 1980, then sold the plant to Taurus. This one has a beautiful  blued finish on the slide, ambidextrous safety/decock levers on the frame, automatic drop safety, reversible mag release. Taurus got a great reputation from these early pistols - fewer locking block problems and better accuracy than the Beretta, plus on slide safety lever to get in the way. This era of PT92 was all forged metal with excellent machining - a lot of folks prefer the old (small cocking slide serations) PT92 to the current Berettas.

I bought 2 of these and decided to keep the one with wood grips. The one I'm selling came as you see it with an extra recoil spring, both Uncle Mikes and Hogue rubber grips, two new 18 round MecGar (the best) magazines and one factory 15 round magazine. I also have a reduced pull mainspring that will lighten the double action trigger pull, holster and a case. This gun has been shot a bit, but has very little finish wear and the bore is perfect. 

The 10 round group you see in the picture was fired in a dark indoor range at 25 yards, resting the pistol on a bench with cheap ammo. 

Please feel free to make an offer and ask questions.

title: For Sale:  Indian Stalker Compound Bow With Browning Bowfishing reel.
postcontent:
I had heart surgery and it has left me with a lot of restrictions. Because of this I'm 
selling a lot of my hunting items / equipment, etc. 

I know you don't really care about my health, but I just wanted everyone to know the reason I'm selling these items.

I have an Indian (Archery) -- Stalker compound bow for sale. This is a right hand bow 
(hold in your left hand and draw the arrow back with your right hand). This bow has an adjustable draw weight of 45, 50 & 55 lbs. (This can be done without a bow press). 

Draw weight is adjusted by turning the limb bolts in or out to align the marks on the 
limb with the marks on the bow. This is what it is a good, solid older bow! 

I WAS IN THE PROCESS OF MAKING IT INTO A BOWFISHING BOW, so it has nocking
points and a new roller rest. Also included is a Browning "tape on "fishing reel" (all metal 
no plastic), the line on the reel has never been in water, and there is about half a spool of line left (kind of forgot the poundage on the line, but its ether 100 or 120 lb. test)... 

There is also a pair of leather gloves so you don't get string burn.

Back when I was able to use this, bowfishing was just beginning to gain recognition and equipment was hard to find. As a result I used to make my on fishing arrows from the solid fiberglass rodsLowe's, Home depot, etc. sales as drive way stakes. 

These were available in Orange, Yellow and White (My biddies and I would each get a different color in case an arrow came untied, we'd know who's it was when we found it, and while we did not call it a safety slide we made our own type of slide out of fishing line and swivels). . . 

Anyway, these stakes / shafts are 5/16 in diameter, 48" long and solid fiberglass with a 5 inch long reflective sticker around one end. There are 5 of these, 

I have cut the shafts down to 32 inches and installed a noc to the ends with the reflective sticker. Two of the arrow have bowfishing tips (all I had left), three of the arrows have 
nocs only. (I usually drill and install a 3/16 roll pin through the bowfishing tip for extra strength / durability, but this has not been done to these two tips). 

Last but not least is a camo soft case made by Kolpin to carry / store the bow and accessories. (The case had been modified by sewing Velcro to hold the arrows and bowfishing reel. 

As stated above no longer able to use this. $100.00 for bow and accessories.

This bow is also on Craigslist if you want to see more pictures.  Thanks for looking.

postcontent:
I had heart surgery and it has left me with a lot of restrictions. Because of this I'm selling a lot of my hunting items / equipment, etc. 

I know you don't care about this, I just wanted everyone to know the reason I'm selling these items.

Because of the restrictions mention above I had to sale all my 60 and 70 lb. draw bows 
and get ones capable of 50 lbs. or less. This is a bow I traded for. It is High Country American -- Supreme LT... Compound bow, the bow is right handed (hold in your left hand and draw the arrow back with your right hand), both draw weight (25 to 80lbs) and draw length (23 to 33) is adjustable. I thought "Good deal"! 

Then I got it home, it is a good looking bow and seem to be a good, solid bow, but once 
I got it home I discovered that the string is missing. Also a couple of small E clips are missing (see photos). Could be other parts missing, but this is the way I bought it and the way I'm selling it... 

The guy at the archery shop said a string would be $60.00 to install a new string! 
Being disabled now, plus not knowing if I'll be able to hunt again or not, I just cannot justify putting that much money into this bow. I thought about buying a Left hand bow (sometimes cheap) but I don't know if I could swap everything over. 

I know I have more in it than I'll get out, but maybe someone out there can fix it or use 
it for parts.... $30.00 and it's yours.

This bow is also on Craigslist if you want to see more pictures.  Thanks for looking

title: For Sale:  Larue Tactical RISR
postcontent:
Finally, a cheek riser that moves back with the charging handle when using collapsible stocks.
It's a fact that some AR's need a cheek riser to get proper cheekweld for raised scopes or rifles with raised rails. It's another fact that standard AR charging handles require a lot of travel, making it impossible to charge a rifle without moving a collapsible stock all the way to the rear. The LaRue RISR solves these problems.

Made in Texas, USA, out of glass-reinforced polymer, the RISR is spring-loaded, and travels to the rear as the charging handle is moved to the rear. When the charging handle is released, the RISR snaps forward. Designed to fit the excellent Magpul CTR butt stock without modification, the RISR only takes a few minutes to install with a phillips-head screwdriver. The RISR does not work on commercial sized furniture and only works wtih Mil-Spec stocks.

The RISR comes complete with all mounting hardware.

For more info http://www.laruetactical.com/larue-tactical-risr-reciprocating-inline-stock-riser

title: For Sale:  LaRue Tactical POD™ (Prone Optimization Device)
postcontent:
Converts your Magpul CTR into a precision-rifle stock
Originally designed for the OBR, the LaRue POD (Prone Optimization Device) places a 1.75" section of MIL-STD-1913 Picatinny rail on the bottom of a Magpul CTR buttstock. This section of rail is the perfect platform for a FUG, raising the stock up to level the rifle when shooting in the prone. The user can pull the FUG into the shoulder for optimum control in stock-seating and can even fine-tune sight picture, by squeezing the grip with the heel of the hand resting on the ground's surface. The section of rail to the bottom also gives additional traction into bench rest bags, when not using an extension. 

For more info: http://www.laruetactical.com/larue-tactical-pod-prone-optimization-device

I have a brand new, in the original box, MeproLight M21 reflex sight that I would like to sell or trade.  This sight has never been used, only removed from the box to test fit, placed back in the box for storage and then removed again to take pics tonight.

This sight is completely self contained and functional.  It uses similar tritium technology as night sights on a pistol, to present a bright bold holographic reticle in even NO or low light.  It also has a light gathering function for daytime operation, which brightens the reticle to produce a usable, visible point of aim even in bright sun light.   The reticle is a bullseye design with a basic ring and dot, which appears to be "projected" onto the target, however nothing is projected beyond the sight and nothing appears illuminated on the business end.  The objective is 30mm and is anti-glare coated as can be seen in the pics.  The base of the scope has an integrated quick detach picatinny attachment.  There's no need to adjust brightness, change batteries, remember to turn it on or off.  There's a reason that these are the primary optic of the IDF; they are effective, reliable, durable, never go dead and are always ready for action.  

Everything that came from the factory is included in this sale; the box, manual, sight and neoprene sight cover.  MeproLight has a 10 year warranty on their sights which includes the tritium illumination.  This optic was purchased new by me in 2010 for a project that I eventually changed directions with.  It was never used and is still in 100% new condition and is every bit as bright as it was the day I got it.

There appears to be what may be a very light crack in the right neck of the butt stock near the frame, but there is no separation when I pull down on it and it may be only a scratch (see pic #21). Checkering is very sharp with almost no wear. Metal is rust free with nice sharp edges and only has very minor pitting around nipples, as usual, but none anywhere else. All markings are crisp and clear with the exception of the patent date on the cylinder, which is worn but still very legible (see photo #33). Complete with the original 4 piece cleaning rod stored in the stock under the butt plate. Mechanics are in excellent shape. Action is as tight as it was when it left the Colt factory almost 160 years ago. Bore is clean and shiny. All screws are excellent.
